  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What would be the charges if land lord break the locking period of 3 months?",
  "response": "The charges or penalties for breaking a locking period, often referred to as a \"lock-in period,\" can vary significantly depending on the terms outlined in the lease agreement or rental contract. Here are some common practices:\n\n1. **Forfeiture of Deposit**: The landlord may retain some or all of the security deposit as a penalty for breaking the lock-in period.\n\n2. **Termination Fee**: The lease may specify a particular fee for breaking the lock-in period, which could be a fixed amount or a percentage of the rent.\n\n3. **Additional Rent Payment**: Some landlords may require payment of rent for the remaining locked-in period, either in full or a portion of it.\n\n4. **Legal Fees**: In some cases, the landlord may also seek to recover any legal costs incurred due to the breach.\n\n5. **Negotiation**: Depending on the relationship between the landlord and tenant, there may be room for negotiation regarding penalties.\n\nIt is essential to review the specific lease agreement to understand the applicable terms and any penalties related to breaking a lock-in period. If unclear, it could be helpful to consult a legal professional or a tenants' rights organization.",
